{{Infobox writer | name = Brian Doherty | image = Brian Doherty by Gage Skidmore.jpg | imagesize = 220px | caption = Doherty in September 2012. | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|06|01|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Author and editor | nationality = American | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | main_work = | influences = | influenced = | website = | spouse = | footnotes = }} '''Brian Doherty''' (born June 1, 1968) is an [[United States|American]] journalist. He is a senior editor at ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine.<ref>[https://reason.com/people/brian-doherty/blogs See reason.com]</ref>
==Work== Doherty is the author of ''This Is Burning Man: The Rise of a New American Underground'' ([[Little, Brown]], 2004), ''[[Radicals for Capitalism: A Freewheeling History of the Modern American Libertarian Movement]]'' ([[PublicAffairs]], 2007), ''Gun Control on Trial: Inside the Supreme Court Battle Over the Second Amendment'' ([[Cato Institute]], 2008), and ''Ron Paul's Revolution: The Man and the Movement He Inspired'' (Broadside Books, 2012).
Doherty has written articles published in dozens of newspapers and magazines, including the ''[[Washington Post]]'', the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'', ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', ''[[National Review]]'', the ''[[Weekly Standard]]'', and the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''.<ref name=bio>{{cite web | url=http://reason.com/people/brian-doherty/all | title=Staff: Brian Doherty, Senior Editor | accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>
Before working for the Cato Institute in the early 1990s, Doherty served as an intern at ''[[Liberty (1987)|Liberty Magazine]]'' and wrote on music and popular culture at ''[[The Independent Florida Alligator]]''. As a student at the [[University of Florida]], where he received a degree in [[journalism]],<ref name=bio/> Doherty played [[bass guitar|bass]] in several [[punk rock]] bands, including The Jeffersons and Turbo Satan. He founded Cherry Smash Records in 1993.
Doherty has said that he is a "principled [[non-voting|nonvoter]]" who has "been saved the embarrassment of ever having to feel any sense of responsibility, of even the smallest size, for the actions of any politician."<ref name="reason">{{cite news |title=Who's Getting Your Vote? |work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] |date=November 2004 |url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/29304.html |accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref>
