[[File:Louis-Pierre Anquetil.jpg|thumb|right|Portrait of Louis-Pierre Anquetil]]
'''Louis-Pierre Anquetil''' (21 February 1723 – 6 September 1808) was a [[French people|French]] [[historian]].

==Biography==
He was born in [[Paris]] on 21 February 1723.{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} In 1741, he joined the religious community of the [[Abbey of St Genevieve|Génofévains]], where he took [[holy orders]] and became professor of [[theology]] and [[literature]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} Later, he became rector of the seminary at [[Reims]], where he published the 3-volume "Civil and Political History of Reims" ({{lang-fr|Histoire civile et politique de Reims}}), in 1756 and 1757.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} In 1759, he was appointed prior of the abbey de la Roe in [[Anjou]]; shortly thereafter he became director of the college of [[Senlis, Oise|Senlis]].{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} While there, he composed a history of France in the 16th and 17th centuries (''{{lang|fr|Esprit de la Ligue, ou histoire politique des troubles de France pendant les XVI<sup>e</sup> et XVII<sup>e</sup> siècles}}'') published in 1767.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} The year before, he had obtained the curacy or priory of [[Chateau-Renard]] near [[Montargis]].{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} He also became a member of the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]].<ref>{{citation |title=Penny Cyclopaedia |publisher=Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge |date=1833 |p=56 }}</ref>

At the beginning of the [[French Revolution]], he moved to the curacy of [[La Villette, Seine|La Villette]] near Paris but, during the [[Reign of Terror]], he was imprisoned at [[Prison Saint-Lazare|St-Lazare]].{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} While there, he began his summary of world history (''{{lang|fr|Précis de l'histoire universelle}}''), afterwards published in nine volumes.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} On the establishment of the [[Institut de France|National Institute]], he was elected as a 2nd-class member of the [[Académie des sciences morales et politiques|Academy of Moral and Political Science]].{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} He was also employed by the [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (France)|French Ministry of Foreign Affairs]],{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} an experience which informed his treatment of the last three kings of the [[Ancient Regime]] (''{{lang|fr|Motifs des guerres et des traités de paix sous [[Louis XIV]], [[Louis XV]], [[Louis XVI]]}}'').{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}}

He is said to have been asked by [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]] to write his 14-volume "History of France" (''{{lang|fr|Histoire de France}}'', 1805). [[Augustin Thierry]] criticized the work as "cold and colourless", and mentioned that Anquetil compared unfavorably to other noted French historians.{{sfn|A'Becket|1907}} The work was compiled at second or third hand{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} and censurable in many respects{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}} but went through numerous editions and made Anquetil famous. It was continued by Adolphe Bouillet in 6 more volumes.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=4}} He died on 6 September 1808.{{sfn|Baynes|1878|p=90}}

His younger brother [[Abraham Hyacinthe Anquetil-Duperron|Abraham]] was a famous [[oriental studies|orientalist]].

