The '''National Association of the Motion Picture Industry''' (NAMPI) was a regulatory body created by the [[Hollywood]] [[Film studio|studios]] in 1916 to answer demands of censorship.<ref name="ah">http://www.americanheritage.com/articles/magazine/ah/1980/2/1980_2_12.shtml</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/encyclopedia/Academy-Awards-Crime-Films/Censorship-AMERICAN-FILM-CENSORSHIP.html|title=American film censorship|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref><ref>Butters. pg. 149</ref> The system consisted of a series of "Thirteen Points", a list of subjects and storylines they promised to avoid.<ref name="ah"/> The organization tried to prevent New York from becoming the first state with its own [[censorship]] board in 1921, but failed.<ref>Black. pg. 30</ref> NAMPI was ineffective and was replaced when the studio hired [[Will H. Hays]] to oversee censorship in 1922.<ref name="DH6">Doherty. pg. 6</ref>

