{{wiktionary|Tomorrow }}
'''Tomorrow ''' is a [[time|temporal construct]] of the relative [[future]];<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pu_c-ooij3IC&pg=PA124&dq=%22tomorrow%22+meaning&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip8KbS_OXRAhUE2WMKHT9BDSAQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=%22tomorrow%22%20meaning&f=false|title=Meaning as Explanation: Advances in Linguistic Sign Theory|last=Contini-Morava|first=Ellen|last2=Goldberg|first2=Barbara Sussman|last3=Kirsner|first3=Robert S.|date=1 January 1995|publisher=[[Walter de Gruyter]]|isbn=9783110141221|language=en}}</ref> literally of the [[day]] after the current day ([[wikt:today|today]]), or figuratively of future periods or times.  Tomorrow is usually considered just beyond the [[present]] and counter to [[yesterday (time)|yesterday]]. It is important in [[time perception]] because it is the first direction the [[arrow of time]] takes humans on Earth.

==Philosophy==
The use of terms such as tomorrow, now and future are part an [[A-series and B-series|a-series]] view which is part of the [[Philosophical presentism|presentism]] philosophy of time.<ref name="eoft">{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of Time: Science, Philosophy, Theology, & Culture |last=Birx |first= H. James |year=2009 |publisher=[[SAGE Publications]] |isbn=9781506319933 |page=438 |url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=9551CgAAQBAJ |accessdate=9 October 2016}}</ref>

==Learning and language==
For a young child, "tomorrow" is "an undefined, infinite time of the idea that time is just an infinite and arbitrary definition of an yet unidentified of what we like to call time, yet the child slowly learns the meaning of tomorrow." The concept of "tomorrow" is rarely understood by 3-year-old children, but 4 year olds understand the idea.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Folberg|first1=Jay|last2=Milne|first2=Ann|last3=Salem|first3=Peter|title=Divorce and Family Mediation: Models, Techniques, and Applications|year=2004|publisher=[[Guilford Press]]|isbn=9781593850029|page=166}}</ref>

